desc: Europe's passport-free travel zone will be welcoming Croatia.  EU countries today voted on whether or not to admit the three nations into the so-called Schengen zone - a pact between countries to abolish border checks for those travelling between their territories. Croatia received unanimous support from the 26 Schengen member states. If you were using Croatia as a base to reset your Schengen day count you might have to find a different base.  And on the other hand it means more borderless travel for those that have secured a residency or citizenship in Schengen zone.  The world is becoming a smaller place.  #freedomofmovement #borderless #moveabroad #sovereignindividual #sovereigncitizen #croatia #schengencountries #schengenvisa #digitalnomad #nomadlife

desc: Michael and Acacia (yeti.the.van) have been living full-time in "Yeti the Van" for over a year now. They're both originally from South Africa and have spent the majority of their first year in Yeti exploring their own country and region.  In this video, Michael and Acacia want to share a little bit about their story and why they chose to live full-time in a van.  In May 2021 they started their nomadic journey living in a small Suzuki SUV. This move was done for them to begin exploring and traveling but also for them to start saving up to be able to afford Yeti.  Michael and Acacia are professional videographers and photographers and find that their nomadic lifestyle has allowed their business to expand.  This video was brought to you by Orion by Up-Switch. It is a fully integrated Nintendo Switch Portable HD 11.6 inch IPS Monitor which is perfect for gaming on the road. ['â€œBeruntung banget bisa kerja remoteâ€', 'â€œBeruntung banget bisa hidup ala digital nomadâ€', 'â€œBeruntung banget bisa keliling dunia di usia mudaâ€', 'Funny if they think
I got it all by â€œluckâ€', 'Sebelum kuliah, gue ga pernah ngerasain ke luar negeri. Simply ya ga punya uang buat itu.', 'So, back in college, I worked hard to achieve my dream to travel the world for free.', 'I donâ€™t have the money?
At least I have the brain. Something yg semua orang punya dan bisa dikembangin, diusahakan.', 'Berusaha ikut lomba/konferensi/research internasional biar bisa ke luar negeri. Keterima! Lolos!
But still, I donâ€™t have enough money or get enough scholarships untuk cover semuanya', 'Gue nggak punya background business sama sekali. Dan sebagai anak semester 3 wkt itu gue harus pitching proposal & project gue untuk didanai di depan banyak bos besar multinational companies.', 'Akhirnya gue berusaha cari sponsorship sendiri ke perusahaan2 & lembaga2 tanpa ada yg ajarin gue.', 'Akhirnya selama gue kuliah, gue bisa pergi ke 10+ negara FOR FREE hasil dari sponsorship & scholarship yg gue usahakan tadi. Ke negara2 itu pun utamanya bukan untuk traveling tapi untuk mengharumkan nama Indonesia dg kemampuan gue.', 'Sejak itu gue semakin pengen menjelajahi dunia.
I wanna explore the world and be the global citizen!', 'And now Iâ€™m working remotely & adopt a digital nomad lifestyle. Sesuatu yg masih asing buat banyak org terutama di Indo.', 'Nope :)
Prestasi itu pun hasil kerja keras yg panjang. Itu pun apakah gue sekali langsung dapet kerja remote?

No. Ada ribuan rejections dan pengalaman pahit yg harus gue lewati.', 'Banyak yg kira semua hanya karna gue berprestasi â€œdari sananyaâ€?', 'But what did I do?
I KEEP GOING', 'YOU WANT MY LIFE.

BUT DO YOU WANT MY PROCESS TOO??'], ['â€œLUCKYâ€']

stickersText:
['My story of how I became a Digital Nomad (PART 1)', 'I got fired from my agency job in NYC while I was living paycheck to paycheck.

I couldnâ€™t afford to live there without a job, but I felt SO burned & I really didnâ€™t want another corporate jobâ€¦', 'All I wanted was to TRAVEL but was broke. 
I sold my stuff, got my security deposit back from my apt, spent a month working odd jobs, and booked a 1-way ticket to THAILAND.', 'My original plan was to teach English but I ended up getting an amazing job editing a magazine instead!! ğŸ˜ (I NEVER wouldâ€™ve been given that opportunity in NYC but in Thailand businesses need people with my skills!)', 'My career took off in Thailand! I made friends from all over the world, I lived in luxury on the 27th floor with a private gym and poolâ€¦ my life was glamorous AF (& really f*ing fun). ', 'Thenâ€¦ there were 3 major tragedies at home ğŸ’” I moved back to the US without a plan.  I tried to fit in, but living abroad had changed me. 

I didnâ€™t know what Iâ€™d do next but I KNEW I wanted to keep my traveling lifestyle alive.', 'After a few months of serious soul searching, I landed a new job that was totally REMOTE while I was on a 2-week trip to Costa Rica. I cancelled my return flight home, and stayed with my laptop. 

My digital nomad life was born! ', 'Part 2!', 'Follow for Part 2!  ğŸ‘‰ğŸ»']

stickersText:
['Tau nggak sih kalau WFH itu sebenernya nggak sama dengan Remote Working?', 'Memang sih similar,
sama2 bekerja secara online.', 'Bedanya remote work nggak terikat peraturan atau punya peraturan perusahaan yg bebas terkait tempat & waktu bekerja. Mau kerja di pantai, gunung, negara/kota lain, beach club, cafe, timezone yg beda juga aman.. asal ada internet.', 'Sementara, walau sama2 online, WFH somehow tetap tunduk dg peraturan2 tertentu terkait waktu & tempatnya and biasanya di set untuk kasih suasana baru ke pekerjanya. Cuma, kasarannya tidak sebebas remote working.', 'Dan dengan kebebasan yg dimiliki sama orang2 yg kerja remote work muncul juga life style digital nomad. Lifestyle dimana orang traveling atau hidup berpindah2 di banyak kota/negara yg berbeda sambil kerja secara online.

Definisi full time worker full time traveler ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜…', 'Tapi apakah semua remote worker sudah pasti punya digital nomad lifestyle?
Belum tentu, ada juga yang memilih tinggal disitu2 aja dan nggak traveling kesana kemari, but bekerja secara remote (and thatâ€™s okay too).', 'Kalau kamu lebih suka WFH atau Remote Working (digital nomad) nih? ğŸ˜ğŸ˜„'], ['WFH vs Remote Working

desc: Replying to @generic_user_name_  Finding a remote job that allows you to travel both nationally internationally can be a really tough time especially if you're trying to live the digital nomad or full time traveler lifestyle like I am. There are career search tools online that I was able to find such as trulyremote.co and there are companies that do seemingly hire international remote workers such as Spotify, Zapier and Atlassian.  The other best option is  To choose a career that allows you to travel remote regardless or makes it more likely such as copywriting, freelance work, e-commerce, software development,  Is teaching English online, etc.  My last piece of advice would be to travel to a place and work there like with a Woking Holiday Vusa or to work a contract job in the United States to save up enough money to travel internationally.  Let me know if you have any more questions on working remotely internationally and I hope this helps! #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlifestyle #fulltimetravel #fulltimetraveler #fulltimetravelers #remotejobs #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadjobs #remotejobsearch

desc: when i shared the places i lived in my 20â€™s in a post last week, I had a lot of qâ€™s asking howâ€¦ and more importantly I noticed that there was perhaps a misconception that you need a lot of money to be able to do it, which (whilst helpful of course) definitely isnâ€™t a must! Straight after university I left the UK for New York, with only small amount in the bank but a biggg desire to experience living everywhere iâ€™d ever dreamed of before iâ€™d have to â€˜settle downâ€™ in one stable job. and by either making money while abroad or finding ways to live there while spending almost nothing, i managed to moved to six countries throughout my entire 20â€™s. for the most part, it did mean living pretty minimally, but the experiences were anything but âœ¨ğŸ«¶ğŸ½ i would also like to add one thing though - if i was 20 again in this era right now, i would go straight to finding ways i can become a digital nomad to be able to travel freely long term whilst earning money online (which is what i do now too). BUT, if you just want to dip your toes into experiencing life somewhere else / make your first move solo (almost for free), then these are some great things that absolutely anyone can do, no matter who you are or how much money you have.  if you feel that pull to travel, youâ€™ll find a way and i hope this post reaches some budding serial expats and offers some inspiration âœ¨ . . . . . #c#createyourdreamlifes#slowtravellerm#madetottravelf#freedomlifestylef#freedomlifel#lifejourneya#authenticexperiencel#localfindsh#hiddengemss#slowtravelf#founderstoryd#digitalnomadlifestyled#digitalnomadlife#f#freespiritf#fulltimetravellerw#womentravelsolos#solofemaletravel#m#madeformores#spiritualgrowthjourneys#selftruste#expatlifea#aupairlifea#aupairparisi#internlifei#internabroadl#lifeabroadl#liveabroads#serialexpatpersonalgrowthjourney

desc: I donâ€™t support communism, in fact I hate it because thatâ€™s the reason why my grandmother had to escape Hungary back in 1956 with my mother in her arms through hills and wire.  However, the remains of Buzludzha are impressive not only for the shape and size but for the psychological effect it has on you as youâ€™re approaching it and you get close to it. From the distance it looks like a spaceship thatâ€™s ready to take off and you can barely notice the bad state it is which can be only seeing once youâ€™re next to it when you get to the top.  I will never say this is beautiful but I will say that it is on its own a good example of human legacy that hopefully never comes back again.  #bulgaria #solotraveller #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #easterneuropetrip

desc: The digital nomad Visa is the perfect  Way to see and live in another country if you have a job that is remote or if you work for yourself. These countries will let you live there as long as you can prove that you make a certain income which most of the time is their minimum wage. Here are all the countries that I mentioned,  Norway Bahamas Portugal Germany  Barbados Greece Iceland Romania  Indonesia Italy Spain Taiwan and Mexico.  I also mentioned Australia New Zealand Ireland South Korea and Singapore do not have this program but will let you stay there for a year with a  working holiday Visa which I can talk about in another video.  As a full time traveler and digital nomad and backpacker these are some of the best tools to use to see the world for cheap, it is also a great alternative to the gap year. Which country would you go to? #digitalnomadlifestyle #digitalnomad #digitalnomadvisa #fulltiemtravel #fulltimetraveler #gapyear #travellife

stickersText:
['How I traveled the ğŸŒ as Digital Nomad PART 2', 'I got my first remote job offer while I was on a 2-week trip to Costa Rica.

 I was sitting by the pool on the phone with my new boss and he said, â€œas long as you have good wifi and are online when you need to be online, I donâ€™t care where you are.â€ ', 'I called Spirit Airline to see if I could change my flight to a later date & MIRACULOUSLY I got a full refund! Suddenly I was in Central America with a full-time remote job, no return flightâ€¦ & a party I wanted to attend in Nicaragua!', 'The party was AMAZING. I couldnâ€™t believe I didnâ€™t have to go home after it!

I promised myself there was no way Iâ€™d F* this up & Iâ€™d do anything to be the MOST RELIABLE employee ever. After a month of traveling, my boss was happy & started giving me better projects.', 'I moved on from Nica to Colombia. Then to Ecuador, Brazilâ€¦ at first I was only SOLO TRAVELING but eventually I started  meeting other people who called themselves â€œDigital Nomads,â€ (I never heard the term before!)', 'The more nomad friends I made, the more I felt like my travel lifestyle was sustainableâ€¦ & it WAS.

I ended up living out of my suitcase for 5 years straight! I traveled to 60 countries while making good money & so many amazing friends.', 'After years at my job I quit in the middle of the pandemic to help people become digital nomads too. Now Iâ€™m a coach!

I use my intuitive gifts to determine which remote business they should create & then guide them through creating their biz and setting up their own traveling lifestyle.']

desc: When I was younger I always thought that traveling the world would be a massive expense. Yes it can be, but it doesnâ€™t have to be! Then 6 years ago, I learned how to travel hack! Beating The banks at their own game, leveraging travel reward bonuses to your benefit. The theory is to use a reward travel card on things or expenses you were already going to be purchasing. For me I used it to pay off my student loans, renovation and material cost for my properties, but it can be used for simple things like gas. However, the number one rule is NEVER let the card incure interest, and always have the money to pay off the card. after I learned this, havenâ€™t been able to sit still since! âœˆï¸ğŸŒğŸ—ºğŸ“#tra#travelhackl#balitravela#realestateinvestingg#augustay#diylandlordg#digitalnomadlifestyle

desc: Full time travel does not equal a vacation. It is easy to see full time travelers and digital nomads as well as people on gap years as taking just extended vacations these long elaborate trips where they are staying in nice places they are doing all of the touristy things and seeing the sites. What's important to know is that most of the time that is not the case, people that travel full time do so mostly because they are either already working still and are retaining a full time remote job or a part time remote job that funds this experience, or they are potentially working at the places they're traveling like working for the hostel or for a ski resort, or they've saved a lot of money, sometimes over the course of years to be able to afford the travel they are currently doing. Still though the truth of the matter is that when you are traveling full time unless you use credit card  Sign on bonuses and are travel hacking like I am most of the experiences that you are having are staying in hostels for extremely cheap not paying for expensive hotels like many would on vacation, they may have quit comfy jobs at home and are just living life. It is no longer a vacation it is your life, and that is why people traveling full time aren't spending as much every day because they're not as rushed to see absolutely everything in every place they have the time to take it slow, Eat at street food vendors instead of nice restaurants, take the free walking tours instead of the one's Trip Advisor recommends for a couple $100 And focus on local experiences rather than catered experiences to tourism. Full time travel is about the experiences and feeling the place in its most authentic way not about seeing everything that you can and spending all of your money.  That's my take anyway let me know what you think? And if you want to know how to full time travel as well then follow along and I'll tell you how!  #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #fulltimetraveler #fulltimetravel #travelforcheap #gapyear #gapyeartravel #vacationtips #travelfulltime
hashtagNames: digitalnomad, digitalnomadlife, digitalnomadlifestyle, fulltimetraveler, fulltimetravel, travelforcheap, gapyear, gapyeartravel, vacationtips, travelfulltime

desc: Replying to @lisaserota  Here are all my budget travel tips and travel recommendations for someone going to visit Tokyo, Japan.  1st I would recommend  Going to all the different cities within Tokyo, Japan such as shinjuku shibuya asakusa rapungi and so on.  Then I would also recommend going to Tokyo Disneyland and sea, the studio ghibli museum, the Ramen museum, TeamLABS Tokyo and some of the more popular places like Sensoji temple, Tokyo sky tree, Tsukiji fish market, and the Imperial palace.  As for food I would recommend trying yakaniku and ramen as well as my favorite Japanese chicken Katsu curry, CoCo Ichibanya is great quick and easy for katsu curry but I may also recommend somewhere that isn't a chain that specializes in katsu curry. Additionally, I would also recommend going outside of the city to Fuji, Kyoto, Osaka and Himeji with the JR Rail pass. #tokyotravel #visittokyo #budgettraveller #budgettraveltips #fulltimetravel #fulltimetraveller #digitalnomads #japantraveltips #visitjapan #digitalnomadlifestyle

desc: T I P S ğŸ‘¨ğŸ¾â€ğŸ’» - A couple things Iâ€™ve learned in the first month of my nomadic journey.  1. Ditch the heavy luggage! - I found that packing light is a MUST when you plan to move around from place to place in a short period of time.  Starting in Europe, the buildings are much older and you might find yourself staying on the 3rd or 4th floor with no elevator through multiple cities. Carrying that 50lb hard side will get exhausting even when just trying to pull it along the old stone roads. Once you get comfortable you wonâ€™t wear most of what you bring anyhow so PACK LIGHT, trust me ğŸ™ğŸ¾ 2. It might get lonely - Youâ€™re solo-traveling so of course you know youâ€™re going to be alone, but feeling lonely is a totally different thing to prepare for.  Itâ€™s bound to happen especially if you visit smaller cities where some of the popular apps to meet people arenâ€™t as widely used.  I found that booking a tour of the city or food tour can be a great way to meet others and help feel less alone on your trip.  Also, just getting outside and being around the locals by working at a cafe or having a drink a bar can get you out of a rut if you find yourself in one.  These are just a couple things Iâ€™ve learned so far.  Iâ€™ll continue to share more tips as I continue to travel ğŸ‘¨ğŸ¾â€ğŸ’» What questions do you have about the nomad life or solo-traveling ?
